England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"en":{"about 1415–1457":"about 1415–1457","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1450–1506":"1450–1506","1452–Male":"1452–Deceased","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1450":"1450","1415":"1415","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","about 1415":"about 1415","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1435":"about 1435","1452":"1452","about 1434":"about 1434","1506":"1506","after 1454":"after 1454","about 1450":"about 1450","Petworth, Sussex, England":"Petworth, Sussex, England","Knypersley, Staffordshire, England":"Knypersley, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"Jennete","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a simplified spelling of   Jeannette   or a revival of a medieval pet form of the female name   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeannette","meanings":["diminutive form of <i>Jeanne</i>, feminine form of <i>Jean</i> ‘John’, now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":40,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Jennete Cotton was born about 1415, in England. She married Thomas Bowyer about 1434. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1457, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1415–1457":"umbes 1415–1457","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1450–1506":"1450–1506","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1450":"1450","1415":"1415","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","about 1415":"umbes 1415","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1452":"1452","about 1434":"umbes 1434","1506":"1506","after 1454":"pärast 1454","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Petworth, Sussex, England":"Petworth, Sussex, England","Knypersley, Staffordshire, England":"Knypersley, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1415–1457":"noin 1415–1457","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1450–1506":"1450–1506","1452–Male":"1452–Kuollut","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1450":"1450","1415":"1415","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","about 1415":"noin 1415","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 1435":"noin 1435","1452":"1452","about 1434":"noin 1434","1506":"1506","after 1454":"1454 jälkeen","about 1450":"noin 1450","Petworth, Sussex, England":"Petworth, Sussex, England","Knypersley, Staffordshire, England":"Knypersley, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1415–1457":"environ 1415–1457","1410–1454":"1410–1454","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1450–1506":"1450–1506","1452–Male":"1452–Décédé","1415–1457":"1415–1457","1450":"1450","1415":"1415","1457":"1457","1435":"1435","about 1415":"environ 1415","1455":"1455","1454":"1454","1410":"1410","about 